body:
If you create a verilated object (`Vmy_top`) at file scope, you end up with races and segfaults. For example, if the exit handlers don't run in the right order then we destroy the `VerilatedContext` singleton before trying to erase a scope when destroying the `Vmy_top` object.

I attach an example that I triggered with an OpenTitan block-level test under ASan. This constructed the `Votbn_top_sim` object inside the `main()` function (to avoid a startup race), but I'd still declared the variable as a `std::unique_ptr<Votbn_top_sim>` at top-level and it was being destroyed as part of `run_exit_handlers`.

[asan.log](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/files/7137222/asan.log)

I produced this example with current master (`v4.212-23-gd384a698`), but this has been triggerable for lots of versions before.

I suspect the destruction-time race could be fixed by using weak pointers (so that the `VerilatedContext` object told its users that it was being destroyed and there is no need to de-register themselves). At construction time, it's a bit more awkward. Maybe there just needs to be some static "instance is valid" flag, along with a list of things that would like to register themselves?

Alternatively, maybe this just needs some noticeable documentation ("Don't create a verilated object at file scope" or similar).

For users, the obvious work-around is not to do the silly thing I did: if you must have a globally scoped variable, do something like this:
```c++
Vmy_top* my_top;

int main()
{
    my_top = new Vmy_top();
    // your program here!
    delete my_top;
}
```
